CSS3 Gradients\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl460\sa600\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf2 The CSS3 gradient feature allows you to create a gradient from one color to another without using any images.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl462\partightenfactor0

\b \cf2 Using CSS3 Gradients\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf2 The CSS3 gradient feature provides a flexible solution to generate smooth transitions between two or more colors. Earlier, to achieve such effect we had to use the images. Using CSS3 gradients you can reduce the download time and saves the bandwidth usages. The elements with gradients can be scaled up or down to any extent without losing the quality, also the output will render much faster because it is generated by the browser.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\sa500\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Gradients are available in two styles: linear and radial.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl462\partightenfactor0

\b \cf2 Creating CSS3 Linear Gradients\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf2 To create a linear gradient you must define at least two color stops. However to create more complex gradient effects you can define more color stops. Color stops are the colors you want to render smooth transitions among. You can also set a starting point and a direction (or an angle) along which the gradient effect is applied. The basic syntax of creating the linear gradients using the keywords can be given with:\
linear-gradient(direction, color-stop1, color-stop2, ...)\
\
