\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf2 You can also create gradients for more than two colors. The following example will show you how to create a linear gradient using multiple color stops. All colors are evenly spaced.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl462\partightenfactor0

\b \cf2 Setting the Location Color Stops\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf2 Color stops are points along the gradient line that will have a specific color at that location. The location of a color stop can be specified either as a percentage, or as an absolute length. You may specify as many color stops as you like to achieve the desired effect.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl462\partightenfactor0

\b \cf2 Repeating the Linear Gradients\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf2 You can repeat linear gradients using the repeating-linear-gradient() function.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl462\partightenfactor0

\b \cf2 Creating CSS3 Radial Gradients\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf2 In a radial gradient color emerge from a single point and smoothly spread outward in a circular or elliptical shape rather than fading from one color to another in a single direction as with linear gradients. The basic syntax of creating a radial gradient can be given with:\
radial-gradient(shape size at position, color-stop1, color-stop2, ...);\
